    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the S-1 preamble, here are the key operating metrics, definitions, and non-standard performance indicators for SpaceX\'s three reportable segments:\n\n### **Overview**\nSpaceX\'s operations are managed and reported in three segments:\n1.  **Space:** Encompasses launch vehicle manufacturing, launch services, and Starlink satellite production.\n2.  **Connectivity:** Encompasses the Starlink satellite internet business, including consumer broadband and enterprise solutions.\n3.  **AI:** Encompasses the xAI business, including the Grok platform and AI infrastructure.\n\n---\n\n### **Key Metrics by Segment**\n\n#### **1. Space Segment**\n*   **Mass to Orbit:** The primary throughput metric.\n    *   **Definition:** The total kilograms (in metric tons) of payload successfully deployed to orbit in a given period. This includes customer payloads, internal Starlink satellites, and development cargo. It excludes failed or scrubbed missions.\n    *   **Significance:** A key indicator of SpaceX\'s launch capacity and scalability. This metric grows faster than segment revenue because it includes internal Starlink deployments, for which no inter-segment revenue is recognized.\n    *   **Reported Figures:** Increased from 1,210 metric tons (2023) to 1,699 (2024) to 2,213 (2025). For Q1: 450 metric tons (Q1 2025) to 556 metric tons (Q1 2026).\n*   **Launches (Number):** The count of orbital missions. Context notes distinguish between "customer launches" (primary mission for an external customer) and "internal launches" (e.g., for Starlink). All Starship launches to date are classified as internal.\n\n#### **2. Connectivity Segment (Starlink)**\n*   **Starlink Subscribers:** The core growth metric.\n    *   **Definition:** The number of unique "Service Lines" active at the end of a period. A Service Line is an individual instance of Starlink internet service provisioned under a subscription plan, generally associated with a terminal. An individual or business can have multiple Service Lines. It includes Personal (Residential, Roam) and Business (Local Priority, Global Priority) plans. It **excludes** managed enterprise and government customers (e.g., aviation, maritime, land mobility, government entities).\n    *   **Significance:** Used to assess adoption and market expansion. Growth is prioritized over ARPU.\n    *   **Reported Figures:** ~10.3 million (Q1 2026), up ~105% YoY from ~5.0 million (Q1 2025).\n*   **Starlink Subscriber ARPU (Average Revenue Per User):**\n    *   **Definition:** Service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers divided by the average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period, divided by the number of months in the period.\n    *   **Strategic Context:** The company\'s strategy prioritizes scale and operational efficiency over ARPU growth. ARPU is expected to decline over the next few years due to international expansion and the addition of lower-priced plans.\n    *   **Reported Figures:** $66/month (Q1 2026), down ~23% YoY from $86/month (Q1 2025).\n*   **Additional Performance Indicators:**\n    *   **Network Scale:** ~9,600 satellites in Low-Earth Orbit (as of March 31, 2026), accounting for ~75% of active maneuverable satellites globally.\n    *   **Service Quality:** Median latency of ~25 ms; median residential download speed of ~225 Mbps during peak hours (as of March 31, 2026).\n    *   **Mobile Reach:** Satellite-to-mobile services provided to ~7.4 million monthly unique devices across ~30 countries.\n    *   **Future Capacity:** Plan to deploy next-generation V3 satellites (1 Tbps capacity each) via Starship in H2 2026, enabling a ~20x increase in downlink capacity per launch vs. Falcon 9.\n\n#### **3. AI Segment (xAI)**\n*   **Monthly Active Users (MAU):**\n    *   **Definition:** The total number of registered users who interacted with Grok or X (via web or mobile app) at least once during a 30-day measurement period. Users are deduplicated across the Grok and X platforms based on sign-in traffic.\n    *   **Nuance:** The methodology is an estimate and may not fully capture all duplication. The company also tracks subsets of users based on their use of Grok\'s AI features.\n*   **Nameplate Compute Draw (in Gigawatts):**\n    *   **Definition:** A non-standard metric representing the total power consumption capacity of the AI infrastructure. It measures the scale of the compute build-out.\n    *   **Reported Figures:** 1 GW (Q1 2026), up from 0.3 GW (Q1 2025).\n\n---\n\n### **Capital Expenditures (CapEx)**\n*   **Definition:** Not explicitly defined in these excerpts, but reported by segment as a supplemental financial metric. It represents investments in property, plant, and equipment, which for these segments would include rockets, satellites, ground infrastructure, and AI compute hardware.\n*   **Reported Figures (Selected):**\n    *   **2025:** Space $3,832M; Connectivity $4,178M; **AI $12,727M**.\n    *   **Q1 2026:** Space $1,052M; Connectivity $1,332M; **AI $7,723M**.\n\n---\n\n### **Non-Standard Performance Indicators (Non-GAAP Financial Measures)**\n*   **Segment Adjusted EBITDA:**\n    *   **Definition:** A non-GAAP measure used to evaluate segment performance. It is reconciled to Segment Income (Loss) from Operations. The excerpts do not provide the full reconciliation formula, but it is a key metric presented alongside segment financial results.\n    *   **Reported Figures (Selected):**\n        *   **Connectivity:** $2,087M (Q1 2026); $7,168M (FY2025).\n        *   **AI:** $(609)M (Q1 2026); $(1,237)M (FY2025).\n        *   **Space:** $653M (FY2025).\n\n### **Summary of Exclusions & Clarifications**\n*   The **"Starlink Subscribers"** metric excludes large, contracted enterprise/government customers.\n*   **"Mass to Orbit"** and **"Launches"** include internal missions (e.g., Starlink deployment), making them grow faster than external revenue.\n*   **"MAU"** is a deduplicated estimate across the X and Grok platforms.\n*   **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** is a non-GAAP measure critical for understanding underlying segment profitability, especially for the investment-heavy AI segment.',
