        output='# X Holdings (Twitter) — Financial Information from the Prospectus\n\nBelow is a consolidated retrieval of every discussion point you asked about. Because these mergers were accounted for as **common-control reorganizations**, the financial statements present a **retrospective combination** of SpaceX, xAI, and X as if they had always been one entity—making it impossible to fully disaggregate individual entity contributions from the data provided.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Revenue\n\n### Consolidated Revenue (all periods include X retrospectively)\n\n| Period | Revenue |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 (unaudited) | $4,694 million |\n| Q1 2025 | $4,067 million |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2025 | $18,674 million |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2024 | $14,015 million |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2023 | $10,387 million |\n\n### X-Specific Revenue Drivers\n\nThe document makes clear that **X is the primary revenue engine of the AI segment**:\n\n> *"In 2023 and 2024, substantially all of our AI segment revenue consisted of advertising, subscriptions, and data licensing revenue generated from X, formerly known as Twitter."*\n\n**2024 vs. 2023:** Revenue decreased by **$341 million (11.5%)**, driven by:\n- A **$595 million decline in advertising revenue** due to the loss of advertising partners for X.\n- Partially offset by a **$254 million increase in AI solutions and infrastructure revenue**, broken down as:\n  - **$157 million** increase in X subscription revenue\n  - **$90 million** increase in data licensing arrangements\n\n**2025 vs. 2024:** Revenue increased by **$581 million (22.2%)**, driven by:\n- A **$116 million increase in advertising revenue** as ad spend from partners on X increased.\n- A **$465 million increase in AI solutions and infrastructure revenue**, broken down as:\n  - **$365 million** increase in X and Grok subscription revenue\n  - **$88 million** increase in data licensing arrangements\n\n---\n\n## 2. Losses (Net Income / Net Loss)\n\n| Period | Net Income (Loss) |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | **$(4,276) million** |\n| Q1 2025 | **$(528) million** |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2025 | **$(4,937) million** |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2024 | **$791 million** |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2023 | **$(4,628) million** |\n\n| Period | Income (Loss) from Operations |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | **$(1,943) million** |\n| Q1 2025 | **$27 million** |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2025 | **$(2,589) million** |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2024 | **$466 million** |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2023 | **$(3,505) million** |\n\n**2024 vs. 2023:** Loss from operations improved by **$3,971 million**, driven by the prior-year impairment charges that did not recur at the same scale.\n\n**Net income per share (basic):**\n| Period | EPS (Basic) |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $(1.27) |\n| Q1 2025 | $(0.18) |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2025 | $(1.69) |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2024 | $0.01 |\n| Year ended Dec 31, 2023 | $(1.68) |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Debt\n\nThe document does **not** provide a standalone balance sheet or a gross debt figure in the chunks provided. However, it discusses debt-related items:\n\n- **X Bridge Credit Facilities:** Interest expense for 2024 decreased by **$113 million (6.7%)** vs. 2023, *"primarily due to the debt issuance costs related to the X Bridge Credit Facilities being amortized only through July 2024, the original maturity date."*\n\n- **Interest expense** is described as including *"interest expense related to our borrowings, amortization of associated debt issuance costs, undrawn fees, and finance leases"* and is *"reflected net of capitalized interest."*\n\n- **Related-party interest expense:** **$186 million** for the three months ended March 31, 2026 (vs. $0 for Q1 2025); **$66 million** for the year ended December 31, 2025 (vs. $0 for 2024 and 2023). These appear on the face of the consolidated statements of operations.\n\n- **Loss on debt extinguishment** appears as a non-cash line item in the consolidated statement of cash flows, though no dollar amount is visible in the provided chunks.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Goodwill\n\nThe document **explicitly states** that no new goodwill was recorded as a result of the mergers:\n\n> *"No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded"* in connection with the common-control reorganizations.\n\nThis is consistent with the accounting treatment for common-control transactions, where assets transfer at their **historical carrying amounts** rather than being remeasured at fair value.\n\nGoodwill is mentioned in the accounting policies as an item subject to significant judgment and estimates (*"fair value of indefinite-lived intangible assets and goodwill"*), implying that **existing goodwill on the balance sheet from prior acquisitions (including the original Twitter acquisition) requires ongoing impairment assessment**, but no specific goodwill balance is disclosed in the provided excerpts.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Asset Impairments\n\nThis is one of the most prominent financial disclosures in the document, driven by the **Twitter-to-X rebranding**:\n\n### 2023 Impairment\n> *"The impairment during the year ended December 31, 2023 was related to the impairment of the Twitter brand intangible asset following its rebranding to X."*\n\nThis was a **one-time charge** described as:\n> *"AI impairment includes a one-time impairment of the Twitter brand when Twitter was rebranded to X in July 2023."*\n\nThe 2023 impairment amount can be inferred: since the 2024 impairment decreased by **$3,775 million** (per one chunk) or **$3,712 million / 98.3%** (per another chunk) compared to 2023, the 2023 brand impairment was approximately **$3.78 billion**.\n\n### 2024 Impairment\n- Decreased by approximately **$3,775 million** vs. 2023 (per one discussion) or **$3,712 million (98.3%)** (per another).\n- The residual 2024 impairment would have been approximately **$56–63 million**.\n\n### 2025 and Q1 2026\n- Impairment appears as a line item in the statements of operations for these periods, but **no specific dollar amounts** are provided in the chunks for the impairment line itself.\n\n### Restructuring Charges (closely related)\n- X initiated **global workforce reductions in 2022**, with effects continuing into 2026.\n- Restructuring charges include *"cash severance expense and other termination benefits"* and *"impairment and early termination penalties as a result of consolidation of Twitter\'s various office leases."*\n- 2024 restructuring charges decreased by **$24 million (10.1%)** vs. 2023, as the prior year included impairment on Twitter-assumed office leases.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Attribution to Each Predecessor Entity\n\nThis is the most critical and revealing point: **the document explicitly does NOT provide separate financial statements or attribution for each predecessor entity.**\n\n> *"As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided."*\n\n### What Can Be Inferred\n\nThe document provides the following structural clues but no disaggregated financials:\n\n- **X (formerly Twitter):** Acquired by Elon Musk in October 2022; became a subsidiary of xAI on March 28, 2025. The AI segment\'s revenue in 2023–2024 was "substantially all" attributable to X\'s advertising, subscriptions, and data licensing. The ~$3.78 billion 2023 impairment and the restructuring charges are explicitly tied to Twitter/X.\n\n- **xAI (X.AI Holdings Corp.):** Began operations in March 2023; acquired by SpaceX on February 2, 2026. The document references xAI\'s revenue from Tesla ($2M in 2025, $0.4M in Jan–Feb 2026) and its commercial licensing arrangements ($191M in 2024, $506M in 2025 from Tesla). The Grok subscription revenue growth ($365M increase in 2025) is attributable to xAI\'s products.\n\n- **SpaceX (the parent/predecessor):** Would be the contributor of the Connectivity (Starlink) and Space segments revenue.\n\n### The Common-Control Accounting Barrier\n\nBecause all mergers were between entities under common control (Elon Musk held majority voting interest in all three), the accounting treatment **retroactively combines** all historical results as if they had always been consolidated. The document notes:\n\n- All periods are presented as a single consolidated entity.\n- Historical carrying amounts are preserved (no fair-value step-up).\n- Intercompany transactions are eliminated.\n- Capital stock reflects SpaceX\'s historical equity combined with X and xAI equity at the applicable exchange ratios.\n\n**Bottom line:** From the data provided, one can identify which revenue and cost items are associated with X (advertising, subscriptions, data licensing, brand impairment) versus other segments, but the prospectus does **not** provide a numerical breakdown of total revenue, net income, assets, or liabilities attributable to SpaceX, xAI, and X Holdings individually for any period.',
